The answer by Louis Wasserman is correct. A couple of important points:

 1. The ***java.util*** date-time API and their formatting API, `SimpleDateFormat` are outdated and error-prone. It is recommended to stop using them completely and switch to the [modern date-time API](https://www.oracle.com/technical-resources/articles/java/jf14-date-time.html).
 2. `SimpleDateFormat` does not have a way to specify a time-zone in the pattern. The way to specify a time-zone with `SimpleDateFormat` is by calling [`SimpleDateFormat#setTimeZone(java.util.TimeZone)`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/text/DateFormat.html#setTimeZone(java.util.TimeZone)). Without setting time-zone explicitly, `SimpleDateFormat` uses the system time-zone. You could get the desired result had you done the following

```
    dateFormat.setTimeZone(TimeZone.getTimeZone(&quot;GMT&quot;));
    dateFormat.format(d);
```

